{
  "answer": "In the *Slokantara*, a rule declares specific acts—killing a child in the womb (*bhrūṇahā*), a great man (*puruṣaghna*), a forbidden maiden (*kanyācora*), etc.—to be *pātaka* (sins) that cause one to \"fall into hell, becoming the dregs of the realm of hell,\" while related acts like killing a cow, a young woman, a child or elder, or arson are termed *upapātaka* (secondary great sins).[^1] Likewise, \"there is no sin (*pātakaṁ*) greater than falsehood (*anṛtāt*),\" for truth is the highest dharma.[^2]\n\nIn Cynewulf's *Andreas*, Matthew prays that God send an angel lest \"blood-thirsty beasts, blinded by sin\" perceive him abandoned; \"sin\" (*synn*) here names the heathens' moral blinding that risks eternal abandonment without divine solace.[^3] The disciples likewise refuse to abandon Andrew, lest they become \"wounded with sin\" (*synnum wunde*), loathed across lands for failing loyal service.[^4]\n\nThe terms perform divergent theological accounting. *Pātaka* operates within a karmic framework of graded sins incurring hellish rebirths (with precise hells like Mahāraurava for extremes), presupposing redress via ritual *prāyaścitta* (expiatory penances, e.g., bathing, fasting, or sacrifices specified elsewhere in smṛti), restoring purity and averting further demerit. *Synn*, by contrast, denotes fault alienating one from God (*e.g.*, Cynewulf's poet-speaker \"shackled by sins\" until divine grace unlocks wisdom), presupposing redress not through works but Christ's redemptive suffering, repentance, and faith—yielding eternal heavenly inheritance sans mechanical rites.[^5] The corpus lacks direct cross-tradition linkage.\n\n[^1]: *Slokantara*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-72c837).\n[^2]: *Slokantara*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-bad244).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-26403d).\n[^4]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-0932ba).\n[^5]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-d2e607).",
